content_18: August 21 at 5:44pm Â· Annandale, VA Â· JUNK MAIL & HAWKS. (Full, true story of Move-In Day). Move in - none of my well crafted goodbye happened. I Cried for 2 weeks before drop off, and actually months before if i thought to much about him leaving. I had a nice letter typed and ready with a special gift to put in his pillow for him to find. Woke up at 3 am in hotel before drop off and in my head for 2 hours I composed another which I transcribed on the back of Expedia hotel info on the 8 minute trip to the dorm. T...his 3 page mess was added to the goodbye package along with the graduation card I had forgotten to give him. Fully an hour before our designated good by time he says we are done ( and well yes we really were and orientation is starting ) after he almost ran from me I got an embrace so quick no time to cry., he turned and was gone. I was standing there sort of stunned.  Mike and i moved on to our orientation. Then the sky darkened to a green black color. We joked it was a shark nado and tried to hurry away from the large trees we were near. Moments later a Huge lightening strike had my husband and I jump out of our skins and the hair on our arms stand up. A few paces on we see a huge dead and somewhat smoldering hawk that moments before had been enjoying the view from the Sadler Stadium lights. Deciding to inform someone we head to the Student Center where we fun into  Grants favorite teacher & an alumni who wrote his recommendations (& whose daughter is now enrolling). He assures me the kid is ready and going to thrive. Walking past us is are not one but two  completely distraught girls with helpless parents trailing behind.  So to summarize: bums rush goodbye with no tears, Mike and  I dodged a deadly lightening strike, we missed getting hit by a dead hawk, our son's room is 20 square feet shorter than all the otters and has a leak  and apparently, in my emotional mom state I left him a thought full gift and a jumble of goodbye letters making me look like a teenage girl or lunatic mom giving him junk mail. I have been way to embarrassed to ask if he found them. content_27: August 16 at 2:00pm Â· Annandale, VA Â· Marshall P. Duke, professor of psychology at Emory University. . "It is a moment that comes along once in a lifetime. Each child only starts college once [...] Such moments are rare. They have power. They give us as parents one-time opportunities to say things to our children that will stick with them not only because of what is said, but because of when it is said," Duke says. "Here is what I tell the parents: Think of what you want to tell your children when you finally tak...e leave of them and they go off to their dorm and the beginning of their new chapter in life and you set out for the slightly emptier house that you will now live in. What thoughts, feelings and advice do you want to stick? 'Always make your bed!'? 'Don't wear your hair that way!'? Surely not. This is a moment to tell them the big things. Things you feel about them as children, as people. Wise things. Things that have guided you in your life. Ways that you hope they will live. Ways that you hope they will be. Big things. Life-level things." So plan move-in day, say goodbye at the university's designated time, leave a letter with the words you want to carry your child through the next few months and years, and then walk away. content_5: August 28 at 4:30pm Â· Oakland, CA Â· Gypsy bluesy jazzy folk with Nathan and Jessie, Sunday, September 4, 2:00 Sometimes thereâ€™s such a thing as too much music.  It was late afternoon at the Folk Alliance Region West (FAR-West) music conference, and Mark went down to the hotel lobby to enjoy some quiet time and tend to some email. â€œSo much for quiet," he said. "A couple of musicians were playing there on a whim. Yet their music was so irresistible that I found myself enchanted rather than disgruntled. Giving up ...on my email, I Nathan & Jessieapproached them and asked, â€˜Who are you?!â€™â€ Nathan Rivera and Jessie Andra Smith, better known as Nathan and Jessie, often get that reaction as they play on streets and stages throughout the U.S., Mexico, and Europe. Their jazz-influenced folk and blues, performed on resonator guitars and accordion with multilingual vocal harmonies, is unfailingly uplifting and fun, with a message for people of all ages and cultures. You canâ€™t help but smile when you hear it. See and hear Nathan and Jessie at nathanandjessie.com In a living room concert Sunday, September 4 at 2:00 PM 933 Rose Avenue, Oakland, CA 94611 $20 in advance, $25 at the door (All proceeds go to the musicians) Reservations are required. content_15: Yesterday at 9:30am Â· All of us listen with rapt attention to the Srilanka Minister for Rehabilitation, Mr.MLAM Hizbullah, narrate the gory details of the Srilankan War. His constituency was controlled by Col.Karuna Amman, the LTTE Commander of the east. Eventually Karuna had a fallout with Capt.Prabakaran and both sides had severe infighting in which thousands of LTTE cadres died. The separation of Karuna and his loyal cadres quickened the demise of LTTE. content_17: September 9 at 9:18pm Â· Spent an entire day with the Srilankan Minister for Rehabilitation and Resettlement, Mr.MLAM Hizbullah. He is a 5 time MP representing the Batticaloa constituency in the eastern part of Srilanka.  He is a Tamil Muslim and spoke about the war and how he had to play a delicate role between the Tamil Tigers and the Srilanka Govt. Fascinating first hand accounts of the war. He survived two suicide bombing attempts. Tiba-tiba terima berita dari Lyon, France seorang atlet negara bernama Ziyad Zolkefli telah menang di kejohanan olahraga dunia. Dunia beb!  Lepas saya terima berita tersebut saya tanya pegawai semada kementerian menyediakan insentif untuk kemenangan tersebut. Saya diberi jawapan memang ada. "Tapi YB jumlah yang diberi kurang sebab ini sukan para." Saya tanya kurang berapa. "Atlet para ni dapat 30% dari nilai ganjaran atlet biasa/normal." Beberapa hari kemudian ada mesyuarat Lembaga Majlis Sukan Negara. Saya selaku Menteri dan juga Pengerusi MSN sendiri bangkitkan isu ganjaran untuk atlet para. Saya kata tidak adil mereka terima insentif kurang dari atlet biasa. Saya cadangkan kita tukar polisi ini. Bagi sama rata. Macam-macam hujah diberi untuk menidakkan cadangan saya. "Paralimpik ini baharu." "Acara mereka tak ramai penyertaan." "Paralimpik ini terlalu banyak kategori acara, mudah untuk menang." Nampak gaya lembaga cenderung untuk menolak cadangan saya.  Saya teringat balik pada Ziyad dan pengorbanannya. Takkan saya mengalah sedangkan beliau mengatasi segala kekurangan untuk menjadi juara dunia? Bilik mesyuarat senyap, menunggu Menteri baharu, muda dan mentah menyerah kalah di tangan para otai pentadbir sukan. Saya pinjamkan semangat Ziyad dan saya tanya satu soalan sahaja. Saya masih ingat, saya tanya dalam Bahasa Inggeris. "Do any of you around this table know what it takes to become a world champion with a disability? What it takes to overcome your disability and succeed?" Tiada seorang pun dapat menjawab. Saya sambung, "Baiklah, daripada sekarang atlet Malaysia semua, tak kira biasa ke, para ke, diberi ganjaran yang sama." Terima kasih Ziyad kerana memberi saya semangat untuk mengubah layanan terhadap atlet para tiga tahun lepas. Hari ini Malaysia is one of the only countries in the world yang memberi insentif sama kepada atlet biasa dan atlet 'luarbiasa'.  Our para athletes' achievements and sacrifices must be honoured the same as other athletes. Not 30% of 'normal' athletes. I would not know how to feel 30% proud of them. I only feel 100% proud of our para heroes. They have shown us that yes, they  are not ordinary. They are extraordinary. LUAR BIASA!
